35) holds the capture lock through `capture_environment`, which can scan worktree state and up to 100 commits per branch at [environment.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/environment.rs:299). That’s a concurrency/perf footgun for hook storms, but narrowing the lock safely needs a deliberate read/write race design, not \n[TRUNCATED]\n The branch adds `review_target`, change-id extraction, and target indexing, but most tests inject `ObservedTargets::from_index_keys_for_testing` at [gitmeta.rs:1531](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1531) and [gitmeta.rs:1618](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1618), bypassing the environment capture path. Add one fixture-backed test that creates branch metadata with review/change IDs and verifies capture produces related review/change hits. Current tests prove writer/reader plumbing, not the branch feature’s real source of truth.\\n\\n2. [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1518): `[REDACTED:entropy]` hardcodes hashed GitMeta index keys. That’s implementation-format mirroring inside a behavior test. Keep one tiny golden test for index-key stability if storage compatibility matters, but make the behavior test assert via `find_related_sessions` / stored observed targets instead of exact SHA strings.\\n\\n3. [crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:404): CLI tests use shell `git init` for generic repo setup, and sync setup shells out three more times at [cli.rs:352](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:352). The sync test may reasonably need Git interop, but the shared `setup_repo` should use the same `gix`/test-support style as [gitmeta.rs:1143](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1143). This is small brittleness with no behavioral upside.\\n\\n**Document / Ignore**\\n\\n- [crates/but-agentlog/src/capture